    },
    {
      "_type": "block",
      "style": "normal",
      "children": [
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "People who live in Yupno Valley, in the remote mountains of Papua New Guinea, don’t see ",
          "marks": []
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "the past",
          "marks": [
            "link-0"
          ]
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": " as something behind us—but rather something below us.",
          "marks": []
        }
      ],
      "markDefs": [
        {
          "_key": "link-0",
          "_type": "link",
          "href": "https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-we-make-sense-of-time/"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "_type": "block",
      "style": "normal",
      "children": [
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "And ",
          "marks": []
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "nomads",
          "marks": [
            "link-0"
          ]
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": " of all kinds don’t own a home…at least not one tied to a physical address. They don’t need one.",
          "marks": []
        }
      ],
      "markDefs": [
        {
          "_key": "link-0",
          "_type": "link",
          "href": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6sxCFZ8_d84"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "_type": "block",
      "style": "normal",
      "children": [
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "So much of what we do, think, and feel is tied to our culture. By the places and people we call home.",
          "marks": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "_type": "block",
      "style": "normal",
      "children": [
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "So much so that it’s easy—and terribly tempting—to confuse (our) culture with what’s normal, ordinary, or commonplace.",
          "marks": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "_type": "block",
      "style": "normal",
      "children": [
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "And why regularly confronting things that appear to be backwards is a healthy habit to embrace.",
          "marks": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "_type": "block",
      "style": "normal",
      "children": [
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "Helping us to see what’s right-side-up for a reason (versus what’s normal, but technically backwards based on what we expect.)",
          "marks": []
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
